Here's an example of how to generate a table of contents automatically in a LaTeX document:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{lipsum}  % For generating dummy text

\begin{document}

% Title of the document
\title{Automatic Table of Contents Example}
\author{Your Name}
\maketitle

% Generate the table of contents
\tableofcontents
\newpage  % Start content on a new page

% Sections with different levels
\section{Introduction}
\lipsum[1]

\subsection{Background}
\lipsum[2]

\subsection{Research Objectives}
\lipsum[3]

\section{Methodology}
\lipsum[4]

\subsection{Data Collection}
\lipsum[5]

\subsection{Data Analysis}
\lipsum[6]

\section{Results}
\lipsum[7]

\subsection{Key Findings}
\lipsum[8]

\section{Conclusion}
\lipsum[9]

\end{document}
```

Key commands for automatic table of contents:
- `\tableofcontents`: Generates the table of contents
- Sectioning commands like `\section`, `\subsection` automatically create entries

Compile twice to ensure correct referencing.

Here's a comprehensive LaTeX code to draw a chessboard using the FEN notation:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{chess}
\usepackage{xskak}

\begin{document}

% Example FEN notation (starting position)
\newcommand{\fennotation}{rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1}

% Draw the chessboard with pieces
\chessgame
\mainline{\fennotation}
\showboard

\end{document}
```

Alternative method using `skak` package:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{skak}

\begin{document}

% Example FEN notation (starting position)
\newcommand{\fennotation}{rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1}

% Draw the chessboard with pieces
\fenboard{\fennotation}
\showboard

\end{document}
```

More advanced method with customization:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{xskak}
\usepackage{tikz}
\usepackage{xcolor}

\begin{document}

% Function to draw chessboard from FEN
\newcommand{\drawchessboardfromfen}[1]{%
    \chessboard[
        color=white,
        colorbackwhite=white,
        colorbackblack=black!10,
        showmover=false,
        pgfstyle=straightmove,
        backref=true
    ]
    \fenboard{#1}
    \showboard
}

% Example FEN notations
\section{Starting Position}
\drawchessboardfromfen{rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1}

\section{Mid-game Position}
\drawchessboardfromfen{r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 1}

\end{document}
```

Key points:
1. Requires `chess`, `xskak`, or `skak` packages
2. FEN notation represents board state
3. Can customize board appearance
4. Easy to input different board positions

Choose the method that best fits your specific LaTeX setup and requirements.
